commentText: Retired LEO, 25 years. I left in disgust with my department and the profession as a whole. I've read a lot of comments about senior command staff being the biggest problem. I totally agree. The world thinks so much of police, but they have no idea what it is really like. They have no idea what people will do to each other to get promoted,  to get that special detail, to get that detective position. People would always say to me, "you guys don't get paid enough..." You are correct. But not for the reasons you think. I carried a gun, wore body armor and was trained to deal with all sorts of threats from domestic encounters, three hundred pound drunks, meth heads and active shooters. But there is no armor, no training that can protect you from a weaponized administration. The world would be shocked at the things I have seen.  But now I have a nice job and get a check every month from my department's retirement that reminds me that I don't have those problems any more.   All the best, young lady.  You got out alive.

commentText: Today layoffs have nothing to do with AI. Sure LLMs (and the following models) are going to involves layoffs, but in the 10 next years. The number of organisations who are *already* able to replace humans with AI is very very small. Today layoffs are more about a global crisis, with inflation, a US president disturbing the world economy, the invasion of Ukraine, climate warming (just the beginning...), etc. So sure, AI will take jobs, as robots did in factories decades ago, but it just means more time for other activities, at least with the proper political regime (not all for the already most wealthy).

commentText: I want to make one correction to the lady around 9:17. The word you're looking for is "automated tracking system" or ATS. Examples include Workday and Talio. These are not new and as a 32 year old when I graduated when I was younger I encountered them as well (circa 2015-2016). ATS systems have nothing to do with the impact ChatGPT and generative AI has on the labour market and it's not helpful to confuse the two. People have been complaining about ATS systems for a very long time, even before ChatGPT and the like existed. The time when humans would review applications was a very long time ago, like maybe 2010 or thereabouts.

commentText: AI isn't taking jobs, it's AI speculation that's taking jobs. AI has generally underperformed everywhere it's been implemented, with studies generally showing it makes workers less efficient (which the media should know, considering the high-profile embarrassments they've had). As the for the hype, it's largely driven by a mix of speculation, advertising/marketing, and bad assumptions about generative AI's current capabilities. All that said, the reporter(s) and pundit(s) for this story could easily lose their jobs to AI without anything of value being lost because their claims involve as much hallucination and shoddy information as AI.

commentText: Those Milk-round recruitments are the most bizarre concept I've ever heard - I was 12 in 2008, and by the time I was graduating my incredibly out of touch Mother in Law suggested I go to a 'recruitment fair' to get a job.  Essentially, in the mid-90s when she had been at uni, you would go to a hall filled with top firms, who you would hand your CV to and they would give you an interview. That was it. That was the job-hunting process. It blew my mind that that could ever exist, and I still struggle to wrapy head around what incentive a company would have for using one of them for recruitment, even before the internet.  A lot of people making decisions about the job market still think this is how it works, that you simply show up in a room and get handed an interview with your CV and a degree, and get handed an interview.

commentText: My take from being a grad in a relatively large company that take a lot of grads on (this was Balfour Beatty, ~6 years ago) is that these companies would invest loads of money on hiring grads, and all sorts of activities/training over the first couple of years, and expected them to stay on for years to recoup that cost. But they didn't, as soon as they lost 'graduate' status, they moved on. And the simple reason for that was that they didn't move salaries up enough while we were graduates, so salaries stagnated in highly skilled jobs, and we could see roles for up to double our salaries going on the outside. So I imagine a lot of grad roles have disappeared because companies didn't think they were getting a benefit out of it (staff retention), when in that all they had to do was be a little more proactive on internal progression/salary rises.

commentText: Honestly DevOps borrows from system admin roles and some functions done by software engineers such as compiling, testing and deployment. Before DevOps was a thing in the 2008-2010 era, Software Engineers had to test, compile the code themselves and then throw it over the fence to IT Operations for sysadmin admins to deploy and monitor. That slowed everything down hence why a new practice was created along with a specialty role DevOps Engineer to bridge the gap to make the software deployment more efficient. That was the really the only reason why DevOps exist. System Admin roles will still remain for quite some time but has evolved a lot to cloud in recent years. commentText: It's not dying. I've been a sysadmin for almost 30 years, and technology just evolves â€” and with it, the roles of professionals evolve too. In the case of DevOps engineers, they've often shifted into roles like SRE, platform engineer, sysadmin, or even security engineer. In the end, most of them do a bit of all these things, not always in the best way, but they do it. why? because what we call DevOps are IT professionals, DevOps is a set of practice between IT ops and the developers.  But do you know something?, the IT operation professional are the more versatile and adaptable professionals handling technologies, cloud or on-premise technologies, so they always find the right path where to be when everything change.  Another issue is that many companies aren't hiring dedicated DevOps engineers anymore. They believe that a developer with some cloud knowledge is enough. They see DevOps engineers as expensive and not particularly valuable, until they start having serious problems and end up paying even more for someone who can actually fix them.

videoTitle: how weâ€™re *actually* getting jobs in 2025 #jobsearch
commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.

videoTitle: Dear University Graduates: "It's over"
videoDescription: Tom Swarbrick has a message for university graduates. #tomswarbrick #unitedkingdom #ukpolitics #uknews #university ...
commentText: I went to university in 1977. It was quite unusual then but today I would learn a trade.

videoTitle: Dear University Graduates: "It's over"
videoDescription: Tom Swarbrick has a message for university graduates. #tomswarbrick #unitedkingdom #ukpolitics #uknews #university ...
commentText: When Labour introduced tuition fees, and when the conservative Lib Dem coalition government raised them, they fundamentally changed how universities operate. I work at a university, prior to the tuition fees there was a cap on the number of applicants allowed on each course which was quite restrictive because funding was heavily reliant on limited public money. Tuition fees was a dream come true for the universities, it changed the whole industry overnight. The main goal went from trying to find and attract the best students, to ramming through as many students as possible to collect the 10 grand a year per student fees. Now suddenly anyone can get into at least 1 university, if not their first choice, there will be another one to collect their money. This has led to the rapid growth in the enrolment  of pointless degrees that yield no employment prospects, as well as an over saturation of the market with certain skills that previously would have been scarce. The whole education system is turning into just one big Ponzi scheme

videoTitle: Dear University Graduates: "It's over"
videoDescription: Tom Swarbrick has a message for university graduates. #tomswarbrick #unitedkingdom #ukpolitics #uknews #university ...
commentText: The reality is that universities used to be for the most capable people, now there are lots of very average students at very average universities. Most of them would be far better to get a trade job or work abroad. Government need to look at education as a priority.

commentText: A lot of the comments are saying "oh shoulda gone into the trades", acting like most people did a soft subject like psychology and now don't know what to do. Not so.   I went to one of the better universities for engineering in this country, and graduated with a first in my masters. I remember being told about the degree and it's employability, saying that engineering grads couldn't move for job offers.   When it came around to my final year, me and my friends began looking for grad roles at the beginning of my academic year (September, rolling off in July). I'd been to careers fairs, got my CV down to a page, got a perfect cover letter for each role, researched the company, etc. I applied to around 3 a day for the first three months, slimming down to maybe 1 a day until about May. I must have done about 200+ applications. Some of my mates did 400.   I got 2 offers, not excluding the other two which were scams. In the end, the grad schemes I got were pretty poor.   The whole thing feels busted. Even doing a "hard" subject feels like you've acquired the most basic qualification for applying to your field. After that, it's a soulless numbers game, and if you're not grafting hard from the beginning, you're left with very paltry options. Many people I know stayed on to do post-grad just because the job market was so dire.   And yet, the status quo is still "if you want to be successful, go to university". This current generation are sadly canaries in the coal mine for the commodification of university education.   Right now, the people who have it best are corporate apprentices: paid-for degree whilst working.   The whole thing is a mess.

commentText: Here in Bournemouth, I work in construction. Right after the beginning of the tax year (6th of April 2025), loads of people seem to apply for work. Even in australia you won't get any specialisation of your choice even if you clear both amc exams , the specialities you get are only the seats leftover after all Aussie graduates are taken (doctors are less in australia but so are colleges that produce them)  - and there are few specialities like emergency medicine left for imgs.
